      <p class="kicker">Function first, personality second</p>
      <h1>Characters</h1>
      <p class="lede prose">
        The useful question is not &lsquo;what is this character like?&rsquo; but &lsquo;what does
        this character do to the tragedy?&rsquo; A character is a working part of a machine
        designed to move an audience, so read each one for their dramatic function and their
        arc. Every study below closes by pointing you at the set question the character serves
        best.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="band">
    <div class="wrap prose">

      <h2 style="margin-top:0;">Macbeth</h2>
      <p>
        Macbeth is the tragedy&rsquo;s engine: everything that happens is either his choice or a
        consequence of it. Shakespeare builds him high before the fall, so the play opens with
        him praised as a loyal warrior whose valour serves the state, which is the standard
        model of Jacobean manhood he will pervert. His hamartia is not ambition alone but
        ambition joined to imagination: he sees, with terrible clarity, what the crime will cost
        and does it anyway, which makes him guilty in a way a mere brute could not be. From the
        murder onward his arc is a hardening, from a man appalled by a bloodied hand to one who
        is so deep in blood that going back is as tedious as going on, until feeling itself
        drains out of him and life reads as a tale signifying nothing. That final nihilism is
        the ruin of the imagination that once made him human.
      </p>
      <p class="small"><strong>Key quotations:</strong> &lsquo;For brave Macbeth&rsquo; (Act 1, Scene 2) &middot; &lsquo;I am in blood / Stepped in so far&rsquo; (Act 3, Scene 4) &middot; &lsquo;Tomorrow, and tomorrow, and tomorrow&rsquo; (Act 5, Scene 5)</p>
      <p class="small"><strong>For your essay:</strong> the core of the <a href="/coursework/">masculinity question</a>. Argue his arc as a study of what a violence-defined manhood does to the man who lives by it, and set it against the kingship question, where he is the tyrant who proves what a king should not be.</p>

      <h2>Lady Macbeth</h2>
      <p>
        Lady Macbeth&rsquo;s function is to convert Macbeth&rsquo;s desire into action, and the
        play needs her because he will not move without her. She is the plan and the will where
        he is the hesitation, and Shakespeare gives her the play&rsquo;s most shocking speeches
        precisely because a woman seizing agency in this world can only do so by attacking her
        own womanhood. Her power, though, is entirely borrowed: she cannot strike the blow (the
        sleeping king resembles her father), she can only drive her husband to it, and once the
        deed makes him a king who no longer needs her, her function empties out. Her arc is the
        exact inverse of his: she begins as the stronger, denying that conscience matters, and
        ends broken by the guilt she swore water would wash away, sleepwalking, off stage,
        beyond help. Read on a feminist lens, she is less a monster than a woman destroyed by the
        only route to power a patriarchal order left open to her.
      </p>
      <p class="small"><strong>Key quotations:</strong> &lsquo;the milk of human kindness&rsquo; (Act 1, Scene 5) &middot; &lsquo;unsex me here&rsquo; (Act 1, Scene 5) &middot; &lsquo;Out, damned spot&rsquo; (Act 5, Scene 1)</p>
      <p class="small"><strong>For your essay:</strong> the core of the <a href="/coursework/">presentation of women question</a>. Argue function and reversal together: she is the engine of the crime and its first casualty, and her collapse is the return of the femininity she tried to renounce.</p>

      <h2>Banquo</h2>
      <p>
        Banquo is Macbeth&rsquo;s foil and the play&rsquo;s road not taken. He hears prophecies
        too, and richer ones (his heirs will be kings), yet he does not murder to hasten them,
        which throws Macbeth&rsquo;s choice into relief: the witches tempt, but the man decides.
        His dramatic function is double. Alive, he is the honest soldier who suspects Macbeth and
        so must be removed, and his murder marks the tyrant&rsquo;s turn from single crime to
        serial killing. Dead, he becomes the ghost at the feast, conscience made visible, and the
        founder of the royal line that will outlast Macbeth, a line that flattered Banquo&rsquo;s
        supposed descendant James I in the audience. Fleance&rsquo;s escape means Macbeth wins the
        throne and loses the future.
      </p>
      <p class="small"><strong>Key quotations:</strong> &lsquo;instruments of darkness tell us truths&rsquo; (Act 1, Scene 3) &middot; &lsquo;thou shalt get kings, though thou be none&rsquo; (Act 1, Scene 3) &middot; &lsquo;Our fears in Banquo / Stick deep&rsquo; (Act 3, Scene 1)</p>
      <p class="small"><strong>For your essay:</strong> a strong resource for the <a href="/coursework/">kingship question</a>. Use him as the legitimate alternative line and as the moral contrast that keeps Macbeth accountable for his own decisions.</p>

      <h2>Duncan</h2>
      <p>
        Duncan is defined largely by his absence: he is murdered early, and the rest of the play
        measures every ruler against the gap he leaves. His function is to embody good kingship
        so that its destruction registers as cosmic. He governs by gratitude and trust, virtues
        that a feudal order prized, and yet those very virtues make him vulnerable, because a
        king who cannot read treachery in a face invites the traitor in. Shakespeare uses him to
        make the play&rsquo;s sharpest point about legitimacy: Duncan&rsquo;s murder is called
        sacrilege, an offence against the divine order the king anchors, and the disordered
        world of Act 2 registers the crime as nature convulsing. He is less a rounded man than a
        standard held up for the tyranny that follows to fall short of.
      </p>
      <p class="small"><strong>Key quotations:</strong> &lsquo;There&rsquo;s no art / To find the mind&rsquo;s construction in the face&rsquo; (Act 1, Scene 4) &middot; &lsquo;Duncan / Hath borne his faculties so meek&rsquo; (Act 1, Scene 7) &middot; &lsquo;So clear in his great office&rsquo; (Act 1, Scene 7)</p>
      <p class="small"><strong>For your essay:</strong> essential to the <a href="/coursework/">kingship question</a>. Argue that the ideal king is drawn mainly by his effect on others and by the catastrophe of his loss, and use the Great Chain of Being as your context.</p>

      <h2>Macduff</h2>
      <p>
        Macduff is the play&rsquo;s instrument of justice and its alternative model of manhood.
        His function is to be the hand that fate has reserved: the man not of woman born who can
        undo the tyrant the prophecies seemed to protect. Just as important is what he does with
        grief. Told his wife and children are slaughtered, he does not swallow the feeling to
        prove himself hard; he insists on feeling it as a man, and Malcolm&rsquo;s urging him to
        take it &lsquo;like a man&rsquo; meets Macduff&rsquo;s truer answer, that he must also feel
        it as a man. Against Macbeth&rsquo;s violence-is-manhood, Macduff offers a manhood that
        can grieve and still act, which is why the play lets him win. His &lsquo;he has no
        children&rsquo; is a line whose grief and vengeance cannot be separated.
      </p>
      <p class="small"><strong>Key quotations:</strong> &lsquo;He has no children&rsquo; (Act 4, Scene 3) &middot; &lsquo;Bleed, bleed, poor country&rsquo; (Act 4, Scene 3) &middot; &lsquo;from his mother&rsquo;s womb / Untimely ripped&rsquo; (Act 5, Scene 8)</p>
      <p class="small"><strong>For your essay:</strong> the counterweight in the <a href="/coursework/">masculinity question</a>. Contrast his grief-and-action manhood with Macbeth&rsquo;s, and use him in the kingship question as the loyal subject who restores the rightful line.</p>

      <h2>Lady Macduff</h2>
      <p>
        Lady Macduff appears in one scene and dies in it, and that economy is the point. Her
        function is to make the cost of tyranny domestic and unbearable: after the murder of a
        king and a friend, Shakespeare shows us the murder of a mother and her child, violence
        that has run all the way down the chain from throne to nursery. She also complicates the
        play&rsquo;s politics. Her bitter complaint that her husband has fled and lacks the
        natural touch lets the audience feel the human price of Macduff&rsquo;s public heroism,
        and her protest that she has done no harm in a world where harm is often praised is the
        clearest statement of the moral inversion Macbeth has caused. She is an innocent used to
        indict a regime.
      </p>
      <p class="small"><strong>Key quotations:</strong> &lsquo;He wants the natural touch&rsquo; (Act 4, Scene 2) &middot; &lsquo;to do harm / Is often laudable&rsquo; (Act 4, Scene 2) &middot; &lsquo;I have done no harm&rsquo; (Act 4, Scene 2)</p>
      <p class="small"><strong>For your essay:</strong> valuable in the <a href="/coursework/">presentation of women question</a>. Argue her as the play&rsquo;s other woman, powerless and domestic where Lady Macbeth is powerful and unsexed, and yet destroyed all the same.</p>

      <h2>Malcolm</h2>
      <p>
        Malcolm&rsquo;s function is to restore the order Macbeth broke and to define, out loud,
        what that order is. He is the rightful heir named by Duncan, so the play&rsquo;s
        resolution is the return of legitimacy, not merely the defeat of a bad man. His long
        testing of Macduff in England, pretending to vices worse than Macbeth&rsquo;s to see
        whether Macduff will flatter or recoil, does real work: it lets Shakespeare catalogue the
        king-becoming graces and shows a king who has learned the lesson Duncan died for, that
        trust must be earned, not given. He is more political function than personality, and that
        is appropriate for a figure whose job is to close the wound in the state.
      </p>
      <p class="small"><strong>Key quotations:</strong> &lsquo;the king-becoming graces&rsquo; (Act 4, Scene 3) &middot; &lsquo;Macbeth / Is ripe for shaking&rsquo; (Act 4, Scene 3)</p>
      <p class="small"><strong>For your essay:</strong> the resolution of the <a href="/coursework/">kingship question</a>. Argue that the play defines good kingship most explicitly through Malcolm, and that his caution corrects Duncan&rsquo;s fatal trust.</p>

      <h2>The Witches</h2>
      <p>
        The Witches are the play&rsquo;s supernatural machinery, the force that sets the tragedy
        in motion without ever committing the crime. Their function is temptation, not compulsion:
        they open with a paradox that unsettles every certainty, greet Macbeth with a truth that
        lets his own ambition do the rest, and return to feed him prophecies that comfort him into
        recklessness. For a king who wrote on demonology and a 1606 audience nervous of witchcraft,
        their power was real and frightening, which is exactly why Shakespeare keeps them
        ambiguous: are they fate, or a mirror for a desire Macbeth already held? A note of caution
        on Hecate: the Hecate scenes are widely doubted as Shakespeare&rsquo;s own work and are
        often thought a later addition, so build no argument on them. The three sisters are enough.
      </p>
      <p class="small"><strong>Key quotations:</strong> &lsquo;Fair is foul, and foul is fair&rsquo; (Act 1, Scene 1) &middot; &lsquo;All hail, Macbeth, that shalt be king hereafter&rsquo; (Act 1, Scene 3) &middot; &lsquo;Double, double toil and trouble&rsquo; (Act 4, Scene 1)</p>
      <p class="small"><strong>For your essay:</strong> central to any answer&rsquo;s fate-versus-choice strand, and useful in the <a href="/coursework/">masculinity question</a> (does the &lsquo;masculine&rsquo; hero master his fate or obey it?). Argue their ambiguity as deliberate: they tempt, they never compel.</p>

      <h2>Fleance and the Porter</h2>
      <p>
        Two small parts do outsized work. <strong>Fleance</strong> barely speaks, yet his escape
        from the murderers, urged to fly while his father dies, is the hinge on which the
        play&rsquo;s future turns: Macbeth secures the crown for himself and none of his line,
        while Banquo&rsquo;s survives to found a dynasty. He is a piece of dramatic architecture,
        a promise the audience must remember through Macbeth&rsquo;s final acts. The
        <strong>Porter</strong>, drunkenly imagining himself gatekeeper of hell and welcoming an
        equivocator through, provides comic relief that is not a break from the play but a
        commentary on it: the castle really has become hell&rsquo;s gate the night a king is
        murdered, and the theme of equivocation is spoken aloud in low comedy just after the
        highest crime.
      </p>
      <p class="small"><strong>Key quotations:</strong> &lsquo;O, treachery!&rsquo; (Act 3, Scene 3) &middot; &lsquo;an equivocator&rsquo; (Act 2, Scene 3) &middot; &lsquo;the primrose way to the everlasting bonfire&rsquo; (Act 2, Scene 3)</p>
      <p class="small"><strong>For your essay:</strong> minor figures with clear functions. Use Fleance in the <a href="/coursework/">kingship question</a> as the future Macbeth cannot kill, and the Porter as a way into equivocation and the hell-on-earth imagery of Act 2.</p>

      <div class="box think">
        <h3>Think it through</h3>
        <p>
          The strongest coursework keeps its hardest questions open rather than answering them
          too soon. Sit with these before you write.
        </p>
        <ul class="tick">
          <li>Is Lady Macbeth a villain, or a casualty of a system that gives women no power except through a man? Can she be both at once, and what does the play gain by making us unsure?</li>
          <li>Does Macbeth choose, or is he chosen? Where exactly, between prophecy and murder, could he still have turned back, and does the play let you locate that moment?</li>
          <li>If Macduff&rsquo;s grief is a truer manhood than Macbeth&rsquo;s violence, why does the play still need him to kill?</li>
          <li>Is Duncan&rsquo;s trust a virtue or a failure of kingship, and does Malcolm&rsquo;s caution correct it or coarsen it?</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Take whichever question grips you into a thesis on the <a href="/coursework/">coursework page</a>,
          gather evidence from the <a href="/quotations/">quotation bank</a>, and test your reading
          scene by scene through the guide, from <a href="/guide/act-1/">Act 1</a> to
          <a href="/guide/act-5/">Act 5</a>.
        </p>
      </div>

    </div>
